<b>Rather</b> than always <b>iterating</b> over an <b>arithmetic progression</b> of numbers (like in Pascal), or giving the user the <b>ability to define</b> both the <b>iteration step</b> and <b>halting condition</b> (as C), Python's for statement <b>iterates over</b> the <b>items</b> of <b>any</b> sequence (a <b>list</b> or a <b>string</b>), the order that appear in the sequence.</font></div><div><font style="font-size: 20px;"><br></font></div><div><font style="font-size: 20px;">&gt; div.font: > The for statement in python differs a bit from what you may be used to in C or Pascal.

> Rather than always iterating over an arithmetic progression of numbers (like in Pascal), or giving the user the ability to define both the iteration step and halting condition (as C), Python's for statement iterates over the items of any sequence (a list or a string), the order that appear in the sequence.

> Code that modifies a collection while iterating over that same collection can be tricky to get right. Instead, it is usually more straight-forward to loop over a copy of the collection or to create a new collection.

div.font: > The built-in function range() can iterate over a sequence of numbers and generates arithmetic progressions.
> For instance: range(10) generates 10 values, the legal indices for items of a sequence of length 10.
> It is possible to let the range start at another number, or to specify a different increment (sometimes negative).
> To iterate over the indices of a sequence, you can combine range() and len(). Alternatively, you can use enumerate() for your convenience.
> Printing a range function can show up strange results.

font.span: > range() saves your space by returning the successive items of the desired sequence through an object - iterable (rather than a list) when you iterate over it.
